BT 0 g /F2 16 Tf 93.12 600 Td (Chapter 3: Crate Training Basics) Tj ET
q 0 G 1 w 60 585 m 372 585 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 560 Td (A crate is not a punishment. Dogs are den animals and crates provide security.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 538 Td (Choose a crate just large enough for your puppy to stand, turn, and lie down.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 516 Td (Too large a crate allows the puppy to soil one end and sleep in the other.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 494 Td (Introduce the crate gradually. Toss treats inside and let the puppy explore freely.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 472 Td (Feed meals inside the crate so it becomes associated with positive experiences.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 450 Td (Close the door for short periods while you sit nearby, then gradually increase time.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 428 Td (Never use the crate as punishment or force a panicking puppy inside.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 406 Td (Cover the crate with a blanket to create a cozy den-like environment.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 384 Td (Young puppies should not stay crated longer than their age in months plus one hour.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 362 Td (An eight-week-old puppy can hold it for about three hours maximum.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 340 Td (A properly crate-trained puppy will voluntarily go to their crate for naps.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 318 Td (Crate training makes housetraining, vet visits, and travel much easier.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F1 10 Tf 213.6 30 Td (3) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
