BT 0 g /F2 16 Tf 93.12 600 Td (Chapter 5: Teaching Sit and Stay) Tj ET
q 0 G 1 w 60 585 m 372 585 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 560 Td (Sit is the first and most useful command every puppy should learn.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 538 Td (Hold a treat close to your puppy's nose and slowly move it up and back.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 516 Td (As their nose follows the treat up, their bottom naturally lowers to the ground.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 494 Td (The instant their bottom touches the floor, say yes and give the treat.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 472 Td (Add the word sit only after the puppy reliably performs the motion.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 450 Td (Practice five to ten repetitions then take a break. Short sessions work best.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 428 Td (Once sit is solid, introduce stay by asking for sit then pausing before treating.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 406 Td (Hold your palm up like a stop sign and say stay in a calm, firm voice.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 384 Td (Start with just one second of stay and reward. Build duration gradually.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 362 Td (Take one small step back. If they hold, return and reward generously.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 340 Td (If they break the stay, simply reset without punishment and try shorter duration.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 318 Td (Always release with a consistent word like okay or free before they move.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F1 10 Tf 213.6 30 Td (5) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
