BT 0 g /F2 16 Tf 66.24000000000001 600 Td (Chapter 10: Handling Separation Anxiety) Tj ET
q 0 G 1 w 60 585 m 372 585 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 560 Td (Separation anxiety causes destructive behavior, barking, and distress when alone.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 538 Td (Prevention starts by teaching your puppy that being alone is safe and normal.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 516 Td (Practice leaving the room for just seconds at first, then return calmly.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 494 Td (Gradually increase the time you are out of sight over days and weeks.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 472 Td (Make departures boring. No long emotional goodbyes or excited hellos.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 450 Td (Give a stuffed Kong or puzzle toy only when leaving so alone time means treats.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 428 Td (Leave the radio or television on for background noise that masks outside sounds.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 406 Td (Exercise your puppy before leaving so they are tired and ready to rest.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 384 Td (If anxiety is severe, never leave them longer than they can handle without panic.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 362 Td (Build up slowly from one minute to five, to fifteen, to thirty, to an hour.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 340 Td (Crate-trained dogs often feel more secure in their crate when you are away.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 318 Td (Consult a veterinary behaviorist if anxiety is extreme despite gradual training.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F1 10 Tf 211.2 30 Td (10) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
