BT 0 g /F2 16 Tf 54.72 600 Td (Chapter 11: Preventing Destructive Chewing) Tj ET
q 0 G 1 w 60 585 m 372 585 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 560 Td (Chewing is normal and necessary for puppies. Your job is directing it appropriately.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 538 Td (Provide at least three to five appropriate chew toys of different textures.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 516 Td (Rotate chew toys every few days so they seem new and interesting.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 494 Td (Frozen Kongs stuffed with peanut butter and kibble provide long-lasting entertainment.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 472 Td (Bully sticks, antlers, and rubber toys satisfy the natural urge to chew.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 450 Td (When you catch them chewing something forbidden, calmly redirect to a proper toy.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 428 Td (Praise them enthusiastically whenever they choose to chew appropriate items.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 406 Td (Keep tempting items like shoes, remotes, and pillows out of reach.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 384 Td (Bitter apple spray on furniture legs and cords deters most puppies.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 362 Td (Increased chewing often signals boredom. Add more exercise and mental stimulation.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 340 Td (Puppies chew most intensely between three and six months during teething.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 318 Td (Providing adequate chew outlets means they never learn to destroy your belongings.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F1 10 Tf 211.2 30 Td (11) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
