BT 0 g /F2 16 Tf 85.44 600 Td (Chapter 12: Establishing a Routine) Tj ET
q 0 G 1 w 60 585 m 372 585 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 560 Td (Dogs thrive on predictable schedules. A routine reduces anxiety and accidents.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 538 Td (Wake up at the same time daily: immediately outside for bathroom, then breakfast.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 516 Td (Feed meals at consistent times, usually two to three times daily for puppies.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 494 Td (Schedule play and training sessions at regular intervals throughout the day.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 472 Td (Midday is typically a long nap period for growing puppies. Let them rest.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 450 Td (Afternoon includes another potty break, playtime, and a short training session.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 428 Td (Evening walk provides exercise and mental stimulation before settling down.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 406 Td (Last potty trip happens right before bedtime at a consistent time each night.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 384 Td (Puppies need 18 to 20 hours of sleep per day. Do not over-stimulate them.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 362 Td (Overtired puppies become hyperactive and bitey, similar to overtired toddlers.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 340 Td (Enforce nap times by placing the puppy in their crate with a chew toy.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 318 Td (Within one week of consistent routine, you will see dramatic behavior improvement.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F1 10 Tf 211.2 30 Td (12) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
